metadata.name: Face Hotel #111
metadata.description:
Face hotel is a digital and artistic version of the insect hotels we see while walking in parks.
This project is the result of a 4-hands work by visual artist Guillaumit and coder and musician Morusque.
For many years Guillaumit has been developing a work based on geometrical shapes combined in a personal way with delicate illustrative elements that seem to give his compositions a soul.
After having designed giant art projects in public spaces for collaborative frescoes Guillaumit decided to work in the world of generative art with the same concern of sincerity and singularity.
This canvas is fully generative and doesn't use predefined graphical assets. It has been designed to be viewed in 800x800, press ENTER to save a screenshot or ALT to save a 5x bigger picture.

metadata.name: monopole #65
metadata.description:
Physics is, above all, beautiful.

Inspired by all the things I find beautiful in physics, and the nostalgia I feel for my undergraduate days of learning about the universe. I sought here to explore what can be created with simple graphics showing simple physical systems. 

The vector field shown is the field from a collection of monopoles, such as electrons and positrons or hypothetical magnetic monopoles.

The papers and inks available are those I have on my desk.

A 2400x2400 download of the image can be generated by pressing UP, but this will take several minutes. An SVG download can be made by pressing DOWN and is suitable for plotting (or laser cutting).

metadata.name: Attachment #120
metadata.description:
The simplest of attachments still have elements of chaos.

The most complex may also feel the most secure.

S : Save current resolution
1 -> 4 : Save Low -> High Resolution

metadata.name: The Three-Body Problem #30
metadata.description:
The Three-Body Problem refers to the difficulty in evaluating an analytical expression for an object under the influence of two massive bodies. This work shows the gravitational vector field from two such bodies. Occasionally, lines will also show curves of equipotential in this field, the centre of mass of the system, the orbital paths traced out. The system is periodic and will loop forever.

Press UP to export one second of frames, and DOWN to save an SVG from the current frame.

metadata.name: Skravert #63
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: In a Moment, a Thousand Years #66
metadata.description:
Fragmented time and fractured memories.

=========

Controls:

[1] set resolution to 716 x 1024px (default)
[2] set resolution to 1433 x 2048px
[3] set resolution to 2455 x 3508px (approx. the size of A4 paper)
[4] set resolution to 3472 x 4961px (approx. the size of A3 paper)
[5] set resolution to 4911 x 7016px (approx. the size of A2 paper)

[0] set resolution to current window size

[c] capture a screenshot at rendered resolution

*The higher resolution settings (3-5) can slow down your device, especially on a low-end laptop without a dedicated GPU. Use it only to render and download a hi-res output for printing. For screen viewing [1] or [2] is recommended.



Made with cables.gl, a node-based webgl environment

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: Artifice #254
metadata.description:
This series is is about playful obfuscation.

The fxtext article linked on the main profect goes more in-depth into what is meant by that, as well as the events that led to this collection.

5640 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries. Palettes make up a third of the code.

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (3000 × 3600)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 9000 ×10600 (Chrome only, and may take a moment)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save a png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Alea #7
metadata.description:
Roll the dice with shapes and capture the moment!
Alea, by the way, is Latin and means dice / gambling.

How does it work?

Each Alea consists of 64 objects randomly arranged around a center and randomly differing in shape, texture, and movement. A curated 5 colors palette is picked and used for the textures. The colors are first sorted by saturation to select a reference color. With this, the colors are then sorted again by luminance.

The animation itself is 32 frames long and stops abruptly. It consists of 3 layers. The first layer moves the objects around the center and draws the animated objects. The second uses the first layer and a double buffer to capture the motion blur based on a depth mask. The third is mainly for screen rendering, debugging and behind-the-scene looks.

Features:

- shapes [7] (toruses, cubes, planes, toruses & cubes, toruses & planes, cubes & planes, toruses, cubes & planes)
- palette [58] (based on German Max Magazine covers 1991 - 1995)
- color sort direction [2] (up, down) - sort by saturation
- color sort reference [3] (0, 1, 2) - used for sorting by luminance / background color

Animation and feature selection are based on the deterministic prng Xoshiro128 seeded with the fxhash. This allows repeated playback in the same sequence. The animation is synchronized with frames and not with time.

The preview images are taken after 32 frames.

Shortcuts & interactions:

- spacebar to trigger a spinning animation (or single click / tap)
- `o` to trigger random object change animation followed by a rotation animation (or double click / tap)
- `r` to trigger a random feature change followed by a random object change and rotation animation (or triple click / tap)
- `k` to toggle this kiosk mode (off, 3, 5 or 10 secs)
- `c` to capture an image
- `f` for full screen mode
- `h` to see all options

Available query string parameters:

- size=8000 - sets the base size for width/height to 8000px (default 3000, useful if you want to capture bigger pngs)
- showannouncement - activates the announcement
- kioskspeed=5 - activates the kiosk mode and sets the speed in seconds
- showinfo - activates the info box

metadata.name: Truchet Towers #137
metadata.description:
Curved Truchet tiling is laid down on a 3D plane forming an imaginary landscape of ripples.

The longest continuous line created by the tiling is removed, cutting a path through the terrain.
This occurs within 3D space and may or may not appear within the confines of the canvas frame,
but most likely will appear.

A tower rises up to wherever a circle is created by the tiling. Driven by the random
tiling, zero or several of these may appear within the frame. Shadows differ in each mint.

In addition to working on decorative tiling, Sébastien Truchet worked on canals and sundials,
forming the inspiration for the exploration of shade and shadow in this work.

Mints will have a variety of earth-tone background colors with each perspective of the scene
slightly different to produce diverse results.

As I researched Sébastien Truchet I learned that he worked with hydraulics and canal design,
as well as sundials. This became the inspiration for my new shading and shadowing technique used
in this piece.

For me this piece evokes a sense of agriculture, and connects me to an imaginary
landscape that could have looked familiar to Truchet in 18th century France.

This work was created with my own javascript, utilizing my polyline path helper library I
maintain at https://github.com/markroland/path-helper.

metadata.name: CHAOTIC UNIVERSE #17
metadata.description:
Many people today may find wonder what exactly is happening to us as we orbit and move around our planet. Some might assume that there’s not much in the way of a reason, others might assume that humans are just being lulled into complacency by having their every need met and be self-absorbed in technology. Or maybe those assumptions are wrong, but for those who know about something called Chaos Theory, it is possible - at least in theory - that we are living in the very beginning moments of a process of change which will pop up from nowhere to take over everything as time goes on.

Some would call it a surprise, but I don’t think a surprise is the right word. In fact, I think that it’s closer to bad luck than anything else. Those of us who know about Chaos Theory know that it’s even possible for a small change at the beginning of the universe to result in the formation of vastly different universes and some where we humans don’t even exist.

Now, this is not something like one person acting differently or changes in other people around that one person. It’s not the butterfly effect. It’s more like there were two people and it was 50-50 to either one of them doing something and then, suddenly, one of those people wasn’t there. How would the other person react? Would they take away a piece of food, or maybe that person wouldn’t have said a particular word at a particular time? In either case, even if it was a tiny tiny difference - I mean, who knows what someone did in the past to make this happen - there would be no way for us to know now that that tiny change decided what kind of universe we live in now and what our lives will be like tomorrow.

How would you feel? Would you think it was bad luck or good luck, or something else? Chances are, you’re going to feel the same way. And don’t think I don’t know what you are thinking of doing if the world was to end and there’d be nobody around but you.

Of course there are people who may have thought about doing something when they came across this article. Maybe people will assume that I am crazy for making these claims - which is fine as long as people assume that I am crazy in general. When things like this happen to us all at once, it is really hard for us to make sense of it all.

metadata.name: 3ASF #66
metadata.description:
3 Armonografos Sobre Figuras / 3 Harmonographs on Shapes

"If I had to choose, the harmonograph is my preferred mechanism for making gen art"

The composition works with three harmonographs vertically distributed with 2 pendulums each that draw on black and white shapes. It is a game between the positive and the negative.

Steps-Layers:

1 - White or black background
2 - Draw shape 1 (triangle or Circle or Rectangle) with the opposite tone to the background.
3 - Draw shape 2 (triangle or Circle or Rectangle) same tone as the background.
4 - Draw the 3 Harmonographs. The (inverted) tones depend on the tones of the shapes and background.
5 - Cutting / glitch effect. Vertical and horizontal.
6 - Symmetries X or Y or XY or none are applied.
7 - Rectangles are cut again (yes/no)

// ---

"Si tuviese que elegir, el armonografo es mi mecanismo preferido para hacer arte generativo"

La composición trabaja con tres armónografos de 2 péndulos distribuídos verticalmente que dibujan sobre figuras en blanco y negro. Es un juego entre positivos y negativos.

Pasos-Capas: 

1 - Fondo blanco o negro
2 - Dibuja figura 1 (triangulo o Circulo o Rectangulo) con tono opuesto al fondo.
3 - Dibuja figura 2 (triangulo o Circulo o Rectangulo) mismo tono que el fondo.
4 - Dibuja los 3 Armonógrafos. Los tonos (invertidos) dependen de los tonos de la figura y el fondo.
5 - Se corta / efecto glitch. Vertical y horizontal.
6 - Se aplican simetrias X o Y o XY o ninguna.
7 - Se cortan nuevamente rectángulos (si/no)

// ---
Keys:

[1,2,3] -> change pixel density. Or can be passed via url ?pd=5 6000x9000pix. Be aware for the file size in render. 
[s] -> download canvas capture. Different pixel density, different sizes.
[double tap] -> download canvas capture on mobile
